Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help ease the HLC.
Red meat and chocolate are assumed to be a nightmare for your digestive tract.
However, recent research suggests the opposite: A diet rich in meats and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects some 1.3 million people in the United States and 300000 in the United Kingdom, leads to the infirmity of the stomach, chronic or bleeding, the loss of weight and extreme fatigue.
In order to alleviate symptoms, patients are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at Washington University have found that the main amino acid protein triptophanes contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the tolerance of the intestines.
The leading researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestines keep the harmful microbes from entering the body.
Cells capable of starting an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severe in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacterium in the intestine have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to start these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria called Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal microbiome of the intestine, and the development of cell populations that increase tolerance.
