Russia will have two new territories ahead of socio-economic development - - Abaza - - and - Novotritzk -
The relevant decisions of the RF Government will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the TOR in the territory of the city of Abbas in the Republic of Hakasia have been defined.
In a city where 15,000 people live, there will be a special legal regime for business activities, as well as a minimum level of investment by residents, and a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to bring about 2.5 billion roubles of investment into the city and to create more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which TOR Abbas will have a special legal regime for business, for example, includes farming, livestock production, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government of the Republic has signed framework agreements on the implementation of 8 investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the Territory ' s dependence on the OOO-Abakan mining enterprise -
In January 2017, the authorities of the region reported that Hakasia had met all the conditions of Mineconom development for the establishment of TOR.
Similarly, the authorities of the Orenburg region have come into existence.
There, the town of Novotrázk will also establish an area ahead of socio-economic development.
This will allow the diversification of the monorod economy, reduce its dependence on the AO-Ural steel, create more than 2,300 jobs and attract investments of more than 8 billion roubles.
The list of economic activities in which the new TOOR will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fishing, food production, medicines and medical supplies.
Novatrix became the first of the Orenburg region ' s monorodes to become the TOR.
Recall that the area of pre-development is an economic zone with concessional fiscal conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges, which are created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the resident TOR benefits are the following: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent during the first five years, and not less than 10 per cent over the next 5 years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent over the 10 years, the free customs regime, the preferential treatment of connections to various infrastructure facilities, and the rent benefits.
